@database SAMWRITE
@master "SAMWRITE.1"
@remark "manual page source format generated by PolyglotMan v3.2 available at http://polyglotman.sourceforge.net/"
@wordwrap
@tab 8

@node sect0 "Name"
samwrite - write a file to a SAMDOS diskette 
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"
@{b}samwrite@{ub} [ @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} ] [ @{b}-basic@{ub} @{i}param1@{ui} @{i}param2@{ui} @{i}param3@{ui} ]   [ @{b}-exec@{ub} @{i}address@{ui} ] [ @{b}-addr@{ub} @{i}address@{ui} ] [ @{b}-string@{ub} @{i}name@{ui} ]   [ @{b}-var@{ub} ] [ @{b}-snap@{ub} ] [ @{b}-mode@{ub} @{i}mode@{ui} ] [ @{b}-screen@{ub} @{i}mode@{ui} ]   [ @{b}-over@{ub} ] [ @{b}-prot@{ub} ] [ @{b}-unprot@{ub} ] [ @{b}-t@{ub} ] [ @{b}-b@{ub} ]   [ @{b}-dir@{ub}@{i} directory@{ui} ] [ @{b}-mkdir@{ub} ] [ @{b}-file@{ub} ] unixfile ... 
@endnode

@node sect2 "Description"
@{i}Samwrite@{ui} copies the specified Unix file or files from the current directory on to a SAMDOS disk.  Wildcard characters are not recognised in the given names, since the shell interprets them into a list of Unix files.  Leading pathname components are stripped, so for example a Unix file called /tmp/foo will be written as foo.  This means that MasterDOS directory names cannot be specified by this method; see the @{b}-dir@{ub}@{i} directory@{ui} flag. @{i}Samwrite@{ui} may be used to write files into a disk image rather than a real floppy by setting the environment variable SAMDISKFILE to the name of the image file or by supplying the @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} flag.  If used this flag must be written first on the command line. It may be abbreviated to @{b}-disk @{ub}@{i}file.@{ui} 

@{i}Samwrite@{ui} will allow one or more of the following command line options, in any order, before each Unix file name: 



· @{b}-basic@{ub}@{i} param1 param2 param3@{ui} @{lindent 3}
The file is recorded as a BASIC program.  The parameters are the three length numbers which will be placed in the disk header: @{i}param1@{ui} is the length of the program only; @{i}param2@{ui} is the total length of the program and numeric variables, and @{i}param3@{ui} is the total length of the program, numeric variables and gap. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-exec@{ub}@{i} address@{ui} @{lindent 3}
If the file is recorded as a CODE file (the default), then @{i}address@{ui} is recorded as the execute address for the file.  If the file is recorded as a BASIC program, then @{i}address@{ui} is recorded as the starting line number for the program. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-addr@{ub}@{i} address@{ui} @{lindent 3}
The file will be recorded as having a start address of @{i}address.@{ui} @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-string@{ub}@{i} name@{ui} @{lindent 3}
The file will be given a string variable header and recorded as a string variable having variable name @{i}name@{ui}@{b}$.@{ub} @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-var@{ub} @{lindent 3}
The file must already begin with an array (or string variable) header. It will be recorded as an array (or string variable). @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-snap@{ub} @{lindent 3}
The file will be recorded as a 48K snapshot.  The file must be in Sam snap format (see the  @{i}samsnap@{ui}(1) command) or it won't load properly.  If the length of the file is not 49174 then @{i}samwrite@{ui} will issue a warning.  The file will not be written at all if it has length less than 23. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-screen@{ub}@{i} mode@{ui} @{lindent 3}
The file will be recorded as a screen picture in mode @{i}mode@{ui} (which should be between 1 and 4 inclusive).  Note that unless the file is a spectrum screen picture or contains palette information, the Sam will probably change all the colours to black on loading the picture. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-mode@{ub}@{i} mode@{ui} @{lindent 3}
If the file is recorded as code, @{i}mode@{ui} will be written in the screen mode slot of the disk header in case the file is read back as a screen picture.  Note that unless the file is a spectrum screen picture or contains palette information, the Sam will probably change all the colours to black if the code is loaded as a screen picture. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-over@{ub} @{lindent 3}
If a file already exists with the same name, it will be overwritten. The default is for the program to ask for verification before overwriting a file of the same name.  This option applies to all filenames which follow. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-prot@{ub} @{lindent 3}
All following files will be written with the "protect" attribute on, until the @{b}-unprot@{ub} option is encountered. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-unprot@{ub} @{lindent 3}
All following files will be written with the "protect" attribute off (the default), until the @{b}-prot@{ub} option is encountered. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-t@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Text file transfer. @{i}Samwrite@{ui} will translate newline characters to carriage returns in all files which follow, and add a 255-byte to the end of each, until the @{b}-b@{ub} option is encountered. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-b@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Binary file transfer. @{i}Samwrite@{ui} will write all following files verbatim, until the @{b}-t@{ub} option is encountered. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-dir@{ub}@{i} directory@{ui} @{lindent 3}
All following files will be placed in the named MasterDOS directory (see @{i}samtools@{ui}(1) for more information about directories).  Files will initially be placed in the current directory. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-mkdir@{ub} @{lindent 3}
The next argument does not name a Unix file but will be written to the disk as a MasterDOS directory.  The name can be a full MasterDOS path name relative to the directory currently named by the @{b}-dir@{ub}@{i} directory@{ui} flag. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-file@{ub} @{lindent 3}
This option signifies that the next argument is the name of a file to read, even if it has the same name as one of the above options.  @{lindent 0}


@endnode

@node sect3 "See Also"
samtools(1), samread(1), samsnap(1) 
@endnode

@node sect4 "Bugs"
There is no option for @{i}samwrite@{ui} which allows the resulting SAMDOS file to have a name different from that of the Unix file. If a name is too long for SAMDOS, it will just be truncated. 

The -t option is cancelled whenever the @{b}-basic@{ub} or @{b}-var@{ub} option is used (this cancellation applies only to individual files, not to all files following). 

There is no option for "all the following names are X", where X refers to BASIC programs or string variables with or without a string variable header. 

The 9-byte header (if any) at the start of file number 1 on a MasterDOS disk will contain part of the disk name instead of the correct info. 

@{i}Samwrite@{ui} does not care whether any file it overwrites is read-only. 

There is no "un-over" option. 


@endnode
